WEBVTT

00:00.642 --> 00:05.630
Father, thank you for the opportunity to spend these moments with these brothers and sisters in Christ.

00:05.670 --> 00:06.851
Thank you for these testimonies.

00:07.212 --> 00:15.004
Thank you for the way at which you're at work, at the U of M and surrounding campuses here and among young adults, especially college students.

00:15.484 --> 00:18.809
Father, would you pour fuel on the flame?

00:18.829 --> 00:27.122
I pray that your Holy Spirit would descend in great power on the campus and burn with the flame of your word.

00:27.362 --> 00:30.926
and be fed by prayer and the fellowship of bodies like this.

00:30.987 --> 00:31.868
Thank you for salt.

00:32.368 --> 00:33.249
Thank you for this church.

00:33.890 --> 00:35.773
And would you bless our few moments here tonight?

00:35.813 --> 00:36.894
In Jesus' name we pray.

00:37.895 --> 00:38.256
Amen.

00:42.882 --> 00:56.018
While I was at Furman University in Greenville, South Carolina, maybe one of the most significant passages for me in orienting my approach to God.

00:56.962 --> 01:03.592
and to the Bible and to prayer and to church and Christian fellowship was Isaiah chapter 55.

01:05.034 --> 01:12.266
And I would love to just linger in the whole chapter, but I just want to start with the first few verses of Isaiah 55.

01:12.726 --> 01:25.426
And what I hope here is to talk about a way that we would approach God's word and a way that we would approach prayer that has the mood or the tone of Isaiah 55.

01:26.114 --> 01:27.816
So Isaiah 55 starts like this.

01:28.417 --> 01:30.139
At this point, this is an amazing thing.

01:30.600 --> 01:34.805
God is playing street vendor in Isaiah 55.

01:34.885 --> 01:36.107
You're just gonna street vendor.

01:36.607 --> 01:37.969
They gotta have them at the U of M, right?

01:37.989 --> 01:43.756
Somebody's calling out like, you know, get your Coca-Cola, get your cookies, get your water, whatever, they're calling out.

01:44.477 --> 01:50.204
Maybe this one guy outside the fair, Minnesota State Fair, a few years ago, he said, you got a thirst, come to me first.

01:50.645 --> 01:51.506
I'm your water guy.

01:52.098 --> 01:53.220
I said, I like that.

01:53.260 --> 01:54.021
He rhymes.

01:54.321 --> 02:00.290
If I'm going to buy water outside the state fair for a dollar, I'm going to buy it from a guy who's a poet and knows how to run.

02:00.430 --> 02:01.612
And Isaiah is also a poet.

02:01.632 --> 02:02.373
Here's how he says it.

02:03.354 --> 02:04.396
He says, come.

02:05.457 --> 02:06.579
He's speaking for God.

02:06.779 --> 02:08.882
He's speaking God's voice here, like a street vendor.

02:09.243 --> 02:09.623
Come.

02:10.965 --> 02:13.649
Everyone who thirsts.

02:13.669 --> 02:14.691
Come to the waters.

02:16.053 --> 02:19.698
And you who have no money come by and eat.

02:20.386 --> 02:24.330
come by wine and milk without money and without price.

02:25.531 --> 02:31.258
Why do you spend your money on that which is not bread and your labor on that which does not satisfy?

02:32.098 --> 02:39.266
But listen diligently and come to me and delight yourself in rich food.

02:40.828 --> 02:46.674
Isn't that amazing that the God of the universe would stoop to play street vendor

02:47.458 --> 02:54.427
And that when he does, he would appeal to your thirst and say, I want to satisfy your thirst.

02:54.887 --> 02:59.593
I gave you thirst so that I, the living God would satisfy your thirst.

02:59.954 --> 03:08.224
I made you hungry, not just with a physical appetite, but with a soul hunger that I might feed you with the bread of life.

03:09.626 --> 03:12.850
I couldn't help but hear that in some of these testimonies.

03:13.506 --> 03:19.512
As you would say, you had talked to somebody and they're basically talking about their spiritual thirst without using that language.

03:20.372 --> 03:21.273
I'm thirsty.

03:21.333 --> 03:22.735
I'm looking for something.

03:22.975 --> 03:23.656
I'm hungry.

03:23.716 --> 03:24.817
My soul is hungry.

03:24.837 --> 03:32.324
And the living God in Isaiah 55 says, I made you like that for me.

03:33.605 --> 03:36.948
I put that hunger in your soul, that thirst in your soul for me.

03:37.008 --> 03:40.111
And so you may say, hey, that's great.

03:41.532 --> 03:41.973
I want it.

03:42.473 --> 03:43.154
How do I get it?

03:43.874 --> 03:46.517
What is it like to feed on God?

03:46.537 --> 03:47.878
How do I feast on Him?

03:49.280 --> 03:53.304
And so we need to think practically about what the Bible says.

03:53.324 --> 03:56.347
Does the Bible give us any direction on where we might go?

03:56.428 --> 04:04.837
How is it that God gives Himself to us as water for our thirst or gives Himself as bread to us to satisfy our souls?

04:06.218 --> 04:13.586
And one effort to get at that answer, if we're talking about the various habits and patterns of our life,

04:14.018 --> 04:15.680
I love to call this Habits of Grace.

04:15.840 --> 04:17.482
Julianna mentioned that book.

04:18.023 --> 04:20.947
Sometimes people talk about it as the spiritual disciplines.

04:22.368 --> 04:26.253
That's not my favorite term for it because sometimes spiritual can seem kind of vague.

04:26.273 --> 04:27.755
Is this lowercase spiritual?

04:28.035 --> 04:29.878
It's kind of like vaguely religious.

04:31.059 --> 04:32.681
I like capital S spiritual.

04:33.823 --> 04:35.164
This is how the Holy Spirit works.

04:36.025 --> 04:42.994
The Holy Spirit has some means that he blesses, that he tells us where we should go.

04:43.106 --> 04:44.007
to get God's grace.

04:45.628 --> 04:54.197
Disciplines, as I put the accent on me, with habits of grace or with the old language from the old theologians was means of grace.

04:55.518 --> 05:01.864
The God of all grace means to keep giving us His grace and He appoints certain means.

05:01.884 --> 05:05.087
He tells us how He's gonna keep giving us grace.

05:06.028 --> 05:12.114
And so then what we do in our Christian lives, in terms of our habits or patterns,

05:12.354 --> 05:21.064
posturing ourselves, adjusting our perspective, moving ourselves into the places where he tells us this grace is gonna be coming.

05:21.624 --> 05:24.968
And my summary for it, sometimes you can make a long list of spiritual disciplines.

05:25.468 --> 05:29.433
I remember this in college, I remember reading a book on spiritual disciplines, making a list.

05:29.493 --> 05:30.414
I was like, oh, there's 12.

05:30.454 --> 05:31.795
And then I realized there's three more.

05:31.815 --> 05:33.998
And it's like, next thing I knew is like there's 20 of these.

05:34.598 --> 05:41.586
I'm looking at the list going, I see why people became monks centuries ago.

05:41.922 --> 05:45.165
Because if I did all 20 of these things every day, this can take most of my time.

05:46.907 --> 05:54.634
And so what I've pressed to do is try to get at what are the principles in the many practicals that can help you?

05:55.155 --> 06:02.602
What are the principles of God's ongoing means of grace in your Christian life for your ongoing feeding on the bread of life?

06:02.622 --> 06:05.064
Your ongoing drinking of the living water.

06:05.745 --> 06:08.307
My summary of those is like this.

06:09.889 --> 06:11.410
Here God's voice,

06:12.098 --> 06:24.292
in his word, have his ear in prayer and belong to his body in the fellowship of the local church, committed Christian communities.

06:24.312 --> 06:31.060
You got word, prayer, fellowship, church, committed Christian relationships.

06:31.380 --> 06:33.182
Hear his voice in his word.

06:33.202 --> 06:35.985
You're not just reading a book, checking a box.

06:36.446 --> 06:40.210
You're hearing the voice of the living God in the book.

06:40.354 --> 06:41.255
praying to him.

06:41.315 --> 06:44.059
It's not just offering prayers into the ether.

06:45.381 --> 06:53.151
You are responding to the God who's spoken to you in his word with the response he wants to hear.

06:53.251 --> 06:55.014
The God of the universe stoops.

06:55.314 --> 06:56.295
He says, pray.

06:56.316 --> 06:57.657
I want to hear from you.

06:57.878 --> 06:59.119
Hear from me in my word.

06:59.520 --> 07:00.802
I want to hear from you in prayer.

07:00.862 --> 07:05.928
And then he says, I don't just make you a Christian by yourself, but you're part of a body.

07:06.730 --> 07:10.034
So belong to his body in the fellowship.

07:10.146 --> 07:10.967
of the local church.

07:10.987 --> 07:12.108
There's my little summary.

07:12.668 --> 07:17.393
Now let me give a disclaimer about the approach here this evening.

07:18.734 --> 07:23.138
They told me they said, these students, these student leaders, they're really good at fellowship.

07:24.079 --> 07:24.580
And you know what?

07:25.381 --> 07:26.061
It looks like that.

07:26.081 --> 07:27.443
I've been here for a little bit tonight.

07:27.483 --> 07:28.664
I've seen you guys interact.

07:28.724 --> 07:29.585
I hear the stories.

07:29.985 --> 07:31.727
And I remember life on the college campus.

07:31.887 --> 07:36.831
The college campus is so great for Christian fellowship because you're at your campus.

07:37.112 --> 07:38.053
There's other students there.

07:38.233 --> 07:39.474
You've got events like this.

07:39.778 --> 07:44.563
And like salt meetings, and like Sunday morning church, you have some rhythms in life of togetherness.

07:45.183 --> 07:49.247
And so the college campus can be a really fruitful time for fellowship.

07:50.628 --> 08:02.279
And it's also a great time to learn about how to feed yourself for a lifetime, in God's word, and what it means to respond to him in this relationship called prayer.

08:03.220 --> 08:04.281
That's our focus here tonight.

08:04.822 --> 08:06.684
How to read the Bible, how to pray.

08:07.004 --> 08:09.106
Very simple, and yet,

08:09.218 --> 08:21.051
If God would be pleased to give us a little tweak, a little insight, a little change in perspective, it might be multiplied over the next week, the next month, the next year, and the rest of your life.

08:22.333 --> 08:33.506
And the main focus that I want to give this tonight, if I had one word that I would want to leave with you and have you remember, it's the word enjoy.

08:34.767 --> 08:37.330
That's the verb, the verb enjoy.

08:38.690 --> 08:58.422
I want to help cultivate a perspective, like Isaiah chapter 55, where you would come to this book and unapologetically, shamelessly, you would say, I am here to enjoy the living God.

08:58.582 --> 09:01.226
I'm here to enjoy his word and enjoy him and his word.

09:02.268 --> 09:04.351
I want to enjoy God in prayer.

09:04.411 --> 09:06.194
These are not

09:07.138 --> 09:08.880
duties to check the box on.

09:08.940 --> 09:10.922
These are not mainly obligations.

09:11.562 --> 09:17.428
These are opportunities for spiritual joy, for feeding the hunger of my soul.

09:17.488 --> 09:26.857
And so that's the main approach I want to bring tonight, as we talk about Word, talk about prayer, is the angle of enjoyment, the Isaiah 55 angle.

09:26.897 --> 09:28.798
There's a feast to be enjoyed.

09:29.319 --> 09:32.322
You don't eat a feast out of obligation.

09:32.342 --> 09:34.624
Come to a feast to enjoy it.

09:35.805 --> 09:36.786
Delight in it.

09:37.250 --> 09:38.251
feed on it.

09:39.172 --> 09:47.603
Let me give you a quote from Jonathan Edwards as he talked about how we posture ourselves toward God's means of grace.

09:47.623 --> 09:57.895
If God tells us, I'm going to keep being gracious to you through my word and through prayer and through Christian community and fellowship, then how do we respond to that?

09:59.036 --> 10:00.498
And here's Edward's approach.

10:01.519 --> 10:02.420
Ed, this is a long time ago.

10:02.501 --> 10:07.026
This is 18th century, 1700s.

10:08.034 --> 10:19.287
He says, see if you can track with it, it's old language, persons need not and ought not to set any bounds to their spiritual and gracious appetites.

10:20.588 --> 10:20.888
You that?

10:22.590 --> 10:25.554
You must set bounds to your physical appetites.

10:26.675 --> 10:27.356
It's an amazing thing.

10:28.317 --> 10:36.466
God made the world in such a way and the human soul in such a way that he says, he doesn't say there's any bounds to your spiritual appetite.

10:37.090 --> 10:38.772
for enjoying God, delighting in God.

10:39.653 --> 10:52.249
Rather, he says, we ought to be endeavoring by all possible ways to inflame our desires and to obtain more spiritual pleasures.

10:53.951 --> 11:00.940
Endeavor to promote spiritual appetites by laying yourself in the way of allormant.

11:03.203 --> 11:05.906
In other words, find out

11:06.434 --> 11:14.523
where God is pouring out his grace, where's the waterfall of his grace falling and lay yourself there?

11:15.904 --> 11:19.989
Position yourself to go on receiving his grace.

11:20.009 --> 11:26.636
So the ongoing grace of the Christian life doesn't happen usually.

11:26.676 --> 11:28.358
This is very rare.

11:28.398 --> 11:31.040
I want to seek God's grace.

11:31.321 --> 11:36.306
So I'm going to go out in the wilderness and walk around and maybe his grace will just go fall on me.

11:37.666 --> 11:38.768
I mean, God can do that.

11:38.788 --> 11:43.155
He can surprise us with His grace and bring strange encounters to us.

11:43.175 --> 11:43.976
We're not expecting it.

11:44.657 --> 11:49.284
But He also tells us the ways that He means to keep pouring out His grace.

11:49.925 --> 12:05.650
And if you know that God wired the room for the light to turn on when you flip the switch, or He did the plumbing such that the water comes out when you turn the spigot, turn the faucet, then you engage His means.

12:06.178 --> 12:07.740
And God's told us about his means.

12:09.121 --> 12:10.503
I've spoken, he says.

12:10.523 --> 12:14.968
I gave you a book.

12:14.988 --> 12:21.656
And I stooped to hear with my son as the high priest in the very throne room of the universe to hear you in prayer.

12:22.076 --> 12:24.539
And I brought you together in the fellowship of the local church.

12:24.599 --> 12:30.606
So we're gonna talk here about enjoying God's word and listening with enjoyment in prayer.

12:31.948 --> 12:34.130
Sometimes the early questions, I know,

12:34.530 --> 12:37.454
Spiritual disciplines, I go back 20 years talking to some college students.

12:38.174 --> 12:40.037
I hear this regularly, get questions.

12:40.477 --> 12:41.458
People are gonna ask a question.

12:41.559 --> 12:43.881
Let me just ask a few up front quickly.

12:43.921 --> 12:47.245
Then we'll get into the main arc I wanna share with you of three points.

12:48.247 --> 12:48.807
How often?

12:50.830 --> 12:56.937
My answer is God's word rewards daily attention.

12:57.498 --> 12:59.781
I think in a room full of leaders, I can be surprised by that.

13:01.102 --> 13:01.403
When?

13:02.964 --> 13:04.306
I'll just put my cards on the table.

13:05.730 --> 13:09.996
There is something about starting your day with the voice of God.

13:11.097 --> 13:16.164
There's no Bible verse that says the command like, you must have devotions first thing in the morning.

13:17.786 --> 13:22.773
There is a pattern of prioritizing important things in the early morning.

13:22.813 --> 13:30.924
There is wisdom that comes from what you engage first shapes the trajectory of your day.

13:30.984 --> 13:33.227
It puts you in a certain perspective.

13:33.888 --> 13:35.410
So I think it's wise

13:35.746 --> 13:37.808
Ideally, it doesn't always happen.

13:37.909 --> 13:39.010
College campus is crazy.

13:39.070 --> 13:39.370
I know.

13:40.772 --> 13:43.976
Ideally, first thing in the morning that you put his voice first.

13:43.996 --> 13:45.157
This is one of the things I try to do.

13:46.138 --> 13:46.659
I'm married.

13:46.899 --> 13:47.680
I've got four kids.

13:49.082 --> 13:52.486
So I have five very important voices in the house with me.

13:52.526 --> 13:58.272
And then there's all those other voices in the world that come up on this thing.

13:58.332 --> 14:03.218
And my resolution

14:03.426 --> 14:04.868
or daily commitment.

14:04.908 --> 14:12.580
As far as it can happen, as far as I can do, I want God's voice to be the first voice I hear in the morning.

14:13.220 --> 14:14.663
Now, sometimes it might be my wife.

14:14.943 --> 14:15.724
Good morning, honey.

14:16.005 --> 14:16.626
How you doing?

14:16.646 --> 14:17.927
You got the coffee going yet.

14:18.608 --> 14:21.873
But when I'm up, I'm making a beeline.

14:22.154 --> 14:23.376
I wanna linger in this book.

14:23.416 --> 14:28.283
I want God's voice to be the first voice I hear in the morning, and that shapes the day.

14:28.383 --> 14:29.665
It shapes the trajectory.

14:30.987 --> 14:33.170
All right, here's my three-part arc.

14:33.666 --> 14:35.950
This is mainly what I have for you here in these next few minutes.

14:36.991 --> 14:46.606
And what I'm doing in sharing this is giving you my daily approach to coming to God in His Word and in morning prayer.

14:46.666 --> 14:49.150
And I won't pretend it's for everybody.

14:49.310 --> 14:50.893
You know the story of David and Goliath.

14:51.193 --> 14:53.857
And Saul says, put this armor on and David tries to put it on.

14:53.877 --> 14:54.578
It doesn't fit him.

14:54.618 --> 14:55.440
He's not going to work.

14:55.800 --> 14:57.162
You don't need to wear Saul's armor.

14:57.222 --> 14:59.666
You don't got to do it just like me.

15:00.226 --> 15:04.071
But I want to be real with you in how it works out in one guy's life.

15:05.093 --> 15:06.735
And see what you might glean from this.

15:06.775 --> 15:10.560
See if there's principles here that are transferable to your situation.

15:10.580 --> 15:11.882
And there's different seasons of life.

15:12.403 --> 15:17.830
There's freshman year, there's senior year, there's life after college, there's life in your 40s and your 60s.

15:18.190 --> 15:19.552
There's different seasons of life.

15:19.953 --> 15:26.802
And if you get some of these principles, you can think through, what does it mean in this season of life

15:27.458 --> 15:41.214
to have my life saturated by God's word, to have rhythms of private and corporate prayer, and then to belong to a community of believers who are committed to each other, typically in the local church.

15:42.536 --> 15:44.058
So here's my little arc.

15:44.078 --> 15:46.721
Number one, begin with Bible.

15:48.142 --> 15:49.644
I'll give you the whole arc, then I'll come fill it in.

15:50.465 --> 15:54.610
Begin with Bible, move to meditation,

15:55.810 --> 15:57.592
and then polish with prayer.

15:58.834 --> 16:00.316
So that's what I'm seeking to do in the morning.

16:00.536 --> 16:04.861
I got my coffee, sitting down at my table with this book.

16:05.702 --> 16:07.585
I brought the real thing for you.

16:07.705 --> 16:13.592
I've been reading this version since I was a fall of 2001.

16:14.633 --> 16:17.136
This is the fall of my sophomore year in college.

16:18.178 --> 16:18.919
This is paper Bible.

16:18.939 --> 16:22.663
This is my communion with God, personal Bible for the mornings.

16:23.084 --> 16:24.946
And I come here, I begin with Bible,

16:25.026 --> 16:27.669
I move to meditation and polish with prayer.

16:27.689 --> 16:28.670
I'm gonna move through those.

16:28.711 --> 16:30.152
I'll spend the most time on meditation.

16:30.973 --> 16:32.996
Beginning with Bible, Polish with prayer will be briefer.

16:34.317 --> 16:35.639
So number one, begin with Bible.

16:37.902 --> 16:39.063
This is not just a book.

16:40.565 --> 16:42.968
This is God's library.

16:45.451 --> 16:54.482
And not only are there 66 distinct books in the God-inspired library,

16:54.946 --> 16:58.651
The book of Psalms, we just quoted Psalm 127 verse one.

16:58.991 --> 17:01.494
The book of Psalms has 150 different Psalms.

17:01.554 --> 17:07.322
That's kind of like 150 books or songs within a larger book.

17:08.644 --> 17:14.831
The book of Isaiah, 66 chapters, all of them worthy of your reading and of your meditation.

17:15.052 --> 17:19.037
So when God gives us a book, sometimes we can just think, oh, come on, a book.

17:19.077 --> 17:20.118
You can have me read a book.

17:21.019 --> 17:21.720
I don't need a book.

17:21.740 --> 17:23.122
That's not gonna change my life.

17:23.586 --> 17:25.348
I'm not just saying this is a book.

17:25.388 --> 17:29.413
I'm saying the voice of the living God speaks through his library.

17:31.275 --> 17:34.119
He wants to tell you about the creation story.

17:34.559 --> 17:40.867
He wants to meet you every place you are emotionally in the Psalms, in your highest days, in your lowest days.

17:41.287 --> 17:46.634
He wants to give you four accounts of the life of his son in the flesh among us.

17:46.914 --> 17:50.098
He wants to tell you what it all means in books like Romans.

17:50.338 --> 17:57.647
and Hebrews, and he wants to tell you how Jesus wins and he wins over and over again to saturate your perspective with the book of Revelation.

17:57.947 --> 18:02.393
So beginning to end, this book provides richness.

18:02.493 --> 18:12.946
It is a feast, it is a banquet, and there's a lifetime's worth of discovery in this library.

18:13.747 --> 18:15.389
It's a long banquet table.

18:16.290 --> 18:19.474
Learning to read the Bible is best done

18:20.066 --> 18:21.547
by reading it for yourself.

18:22.769 --> 18:23.990
And you can go study over here.

18:24.030 --> 18:24.550
What do I do?

18:24.570 --> 18:27.273
I do these things, learn these things, do the training wheels.

18:27.293 --> 18:27.753
That's fine.

18:28.674 --> 18:36.622
The best way to do it is to read it for yourself and to do it for a lifetime, which is why it's so important to talk to college students about these things.

18:36.642 --> 18:41.547
This is not about what you can do this year only or these four years only.

18:42.187 --> 18:48.914
You are at a time a trajectory setting time of life where you can begin to orient

18:49.090 --> 19:00.424
with enjoyment on the riches of this book and learn to feed yourselves and be the kind of person who can feed others through the riches of this library.

19:01.385 --> 19:03.067
So the Bible's a library.

19:04.008 --> 19:06.851
But then you gotta choose a plan.

19:06.871 --> 19:11.857
You gotta have a plan when you get up in the morning, you just end up reading Titus over and over, Jude over and over.

19:11.897 --> 19:14.380
First Peter, I think I can do all five chapters of the first Peter.

19:14.521 --> 19:15.762
Maybe you know what I'm talking about.

19:16.034 --> 19:17.335
You've lived college life like me.

19:17.355 --> 19:18.336
What am I going to read this morning?

19:18.356 --> 19:19.357
I'll do another short epistle.

19:20.058 --> 19:28.246
So I learned after a while, it's helpful to have some kind of modest plan that when you come to the Bible in the morning, you've got a plan.

19:29.767 --> 19:34.171
The plan I have, anybody, anybody know how long it takes to read the Bible?

19:34.672 --> 19:35.753
A normal reading pace.

19:36.453 --> 19:37.474
How many hours does it take?

19:39.096 --> 19:39.476
Anybody know?

19:39.496 --> 19:42.619
A little more than that.

19:42.639 --> 19:42.859
It's good.

19:42.880 --> 19:43.400
It's close.

19:44.061 --> 19:45.522
It's about 70 hours.

